    <node id=" Government so far on PCET reform, we will be introducing more formal outcome agreements, whereby institutions might be given by the commission very clear expectations of how they're expected to contribute to national priorities.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: Thanks. We've heard that the HE Act, by focusing on individual institutions, did not encourage collaboration, even for widening access activity. Was this a missed opportunity and how will this be taken forward in the PCET Bill?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: I think we can strengthen our sector by closer collaboration. I think what sets us apart in Wales is that this Government is determined to create a legislative regime and a regulation regime that encourages collaboration and co-operation, which is in stark contrast to the marketisation and the competition that we see being regulated for and legislated for across the border in England. That's one of the reasons why we are going to introduce the new PCET reforms—to create collaboration, not just between different higher education institutes but actually across the sector. So, this is a prime opportunity where we can create a framework that demands and encourages collaboration, not just, as I said, in between individual institutions but across the entirety of the sector. We're doing that" />
    <node id=" more part-time students? Do you think the landscape may change in future and that the 2015 Act, as designed, wasn't equipped for that, and will the next Act, then, be equipped?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: I think it's right to say that maybe the previous legislation didn't futureproof for changes. I'm not anticipating a mass influx of alternative providers, in the sense that we've seen across the border, but we will need to ensure that the new commission has powers to regulate and to futureproof.&#10;Speaker: Hefin David AM&#10;Content: Okay. Thank you, Chair.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Dawn.&#10;Speaker: Dawn Bowden AM&#10;Content: Thank you. We had some evidence from the University and College Union that were concerned about the governance of universities, actually, as being a bigger problem than the regulatory framework in many ways. Can you tell us, perhaps, how the HE Act addresses the issue of poor governance, or is it really just limited to responding to the symptoms rather than the poor governance itself?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Well, I think it's true and fair to say that the Bill does not directly" />
    <node id="1. Regulation and Quality: Private institutions, as compared to public institutions, operate with less rigor and are subject to less regulation. This is because they do not have to adhere to the same standards or comply with the same level of scrutiny. The QAA, in cooperation with institutions, reviews and inspects offshore higher education activities; however, there is no plan to mandate specific review details in the new legislation.&#10;&#10;2. Role of Charitable Status: Many private institutions are also charities, which receive less attention in discussions about regulation. Charitable status is an important reference point for the operation of these institutions. Some private providers, especially in England, have faced issues related to fee limits, quality of provision, and financial management code violations, leading to intervention and sanctions from HEFCW under the 2015 Higher Education Act.&#10;&#10;3. Viewing Private Institutions: When considering the interests of students, it's important to be cautious about tarring all private providers with the same brush, as some may provide high-quality education despite their private status. The new legislation should consider this nuance and focus on the inherent quality of institutions rather than their categorization as public or private.&#10;&#10;4. Managing Risk: With the 2015 Act in place, institutions with stronger track records are more highly regulated compared to riskier alternative providers. This balance should be maintained, as legislation should strike a proportionality based on the amount and nature of public money received by institutions. The new legislation will look to create a system of outcome agreements where outputs will reflect national priorities.&#10;&#10;In conclusion, when discussing private versus public institutions, it is essential to consider charitable status, inherent quality, track records, and the balance between regulation and proportionality based on public funding. The new legislation must strike a careful balance that protects students' interests while fostering an environment conducive to broadening access in higher education." />
