    <node id="1. HEFCW is encouraging a &quot;civic university approach&quot; by providing information, holding events, and offering staff, management, and leadership development activities to create a culture among institution leaders and governing bodies that moves them in this direction. They use informal interactions with various tertiary sector stakeholders such as FE college principals, work-based learning providers, and sixth forms to foster alignment with the civic university approach.&#10;2. Although there is no plan to mandate specific review details in the new legislation, HEFCW and QAA play a crucial role in ensuring the quality of offshore higher education activities. This helps maintain the strong reputation of Welsh institutions and the sector as a whole.&#10;3. The 2015 Higher Education Act has given HEFCW new powers to intervene and enforce compliance when necessary, including issues related to fee limits, quality of provision, or financial management code violations. However, governance issues in the sector are not directly addressed by the Act.&#10;4. In summary, HEFCW uses various measures to foster a civic university approach, focusing on cooperation with institutions and stakeholders. The 2015 Higher Education Act has provided new intervention powers, but there is no return to the block grant allocation system." />
    <node id=" Minister has said, there's a range of ways in which we interact with all institutions that are going to be in the tertiary sector, and some of that is about providing information. So, HEFCW provides information—it sends around circulars, it produces reports and it holds events. There's staff, management and leadership development activity, which can create a culture amongst the leaders of institutions, but also amongst their governing bodies, to help them move in a particular direction. We would hope that's in the direction of the civic university approach that the Minister has outlined. We use those mechanisms and informal interactions with FE college principals, with the work-based learning provider network, with sixth forms and others, and we would want to see, I hope, in the tertiary sector some alignment of those things. When things go badly wrong, there are a range of mechanisms. I think what stands behind HEFCW's comments is that before we had a loan-based system of student finance, there was a system of block grant allocations and conditions could be attached to those grant allocations by HEFCW. I don't think we're going to be going back to that system in the foreseeable future because of the pressures on public finances—&#10;Speaker: Hefin David AM" />
