    <node id=" AM&#10;Content: That's my preference. So, I think the principle—I'd like to think we can all agree around the principle of what a fee and access plan is hoping to achieve, but I think there are better ways of doing it, and I think we should take the opportunity of reform to look at how we can do it better.&#10;Speaker: Hefin David AM&#10;Content: So, with that in mind, I think we're talking about the future of the Bill, the consultation on the PCET reforms closed in summer 2018—with these important issues in mind and things that are currently ongoing, have you had further dialogue since then with key stakeholders like, for example, Universities Wales and others?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: On the Bill or on fee and access plans in particular?&#10;Speaker: Hefin David AM&#10;Content: I'm thinking about fee and access plans as an issue that suggests that there is a need for deep consultation, so with that in mind, with things like that, have you had further discussion?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Oh my goodness me, civil servants in the department are constantly in discussion with a range of stakeholders as we continue to develop legislative" />
    <node id="1. As the tertiary education sector in Wales expands to include more providers, HEFCW must ensure that its regulatory measures remain flexible and effective. This can be achieved by maintaining a balance between formal interventions and informal interactions with stakeholders. Informal measures, such as providing information, holding events, and offering staff development activities, can foster a culture of compliance among institution leaders and governing bodies.&#10;&#10;2. Additionally, HEFCW should leverage its new powers of intervention and sanctions, given under the 2015 Higher Education Act, to address non-compliance issues related to fee limits, quality of provision, or financial management code violations. However, HEFCW should be mindful that these formal measures may not always be suitable for swift interventions, as they can be cumbersome and time-consuming.&#10;&#10;3. To maintain flexibility, HEFCW could develop a risk-based approach to regulation, focusing on riskier alternative providers while ensuring that stronger track record institutions face appropriate levels of scrutiny. This way, the regulator can allocate resources more efficiently and effectively, addressing issues proactively rather than reactively.&#10;&#10;4. Lastly, in order to promote collaboration and avoid duplication, HEFCW should work on creating a framework that encourages partnerships between different parts of post-compulsory education. This will help create a seamless passage for students moving between various educational opportunities and minimize barriers to entry." />
    <node id="The Welsh government has not identified an urgent reason to regulate part-time and postgraduate fees because the current Act, the 2015 Act, does not permit fee regulation of postgraduate courses, other than PGCE courses for IT purposes. In the case of part-time courses, the government is currently content that fee levels are not exceeding the amount of student support made available by the Welsh Government. The success of attracting people to postgraduate and part-time study in Wales is due to the reforms to student finance. However, the government will keep this under review, recognizing that there are difficulties around deciding and introducing fee limits on postgraduate courses. There is no current review of this policy mentioned in the transcript." />
    <node id="&#10;Content: Just turning finally to part-time fees and postgraduate fees, do you have an intention to regulate this part in the new legislation?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: I have to say that, at present, we've not identified an urgent reason to designate these courses as qualifying courses for the purposes of a fee limit. And there are a number of reasons for that. Actually, the current Act—the 2015 Act—does not permit the fee regulation of postgraduate courses, other than PGCE courses for IT purposes. In the case of part-time courses, I'm currently content that fee levels are not exceeding the amount of student support made available by the Welsh Government. So, I think we are, at this moment, relaxed about that, and there are some difficulties around deciding and introducing fee limits on postgraduate courses. I think what's really important to me is the success at the moment of attracting people to postgraduate and part-time study in Wales, as a result of our reforms to student finance. But, clearly, we'll need to keep that under review. But, at this current moment, the Act precludes fee regulation in some areas and there's not a pressing policy need that we've identified to date." />
