    <node id="Based on the meeting transcript, the Welsh Government does not explicitly mention any specific measures to address the gap between early conversations and the possibility of institutions going bankrupt in the tertiary education sector. However, they do plan to review and potentially amend or replace the Higher Education (Wales) Act 2015 through the post-compulsory education and training Bill. This new bill may include provisions to ensure appropriate regulation and accountability of institutions for their public funding and privileges, which could potentially address some of the concerns around institutional bankruptcy. The government also emphasizes the importance of a positive working relationship with higher education institutions and HEFCW, as well as using mechanisms like remit letters to clearly articulate national priorities." />
    <node id="Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Good morning, everyone. Welcome to the Children, Young People and Education Committee. We've received apologies for absence from Suzy Davies and there is no substitute. Janet Finch-Saunders is joining us from the Assembly offices in Colwyn Bay via video conference. Can I ask Members if there are any declarations of interest, please? No. Okay. Item 2, then, this morning is a post-legislative scrutiny session on the Higher Education (Wales) Act 2015. I'm very pleased to welcome Kirsty Williams AM, Minister for Education, and Huw Morris, who is director of the skills, higher education and lifelong learning group in Welsh Government. Thank you, both, for attending, and thank you for the paper that you provided in advance. I will just start the questioning by asking whether you are planning to repeal the 2015 higher education Act, or will it be amended by the post-compulsory education and training Bill?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Thank you very much, Chair. I'm very pleased to be with the committee again this morning, although it's in slightly unusual circumstances. As a piece of post-legislative scrutiny, this was a Bill" />
    <node id="1. The Welsh government is proposing to move towards a single quality assurance body for the tertiary education sector, which would include higher education, further education, and work-based learning. This change aims to ensure compatibility and coherence between quality assurance regimes as they converge in the tertiary sector, addressing emerging trends in higher education.&#10;&#10;2. The new Bill will address issues related to transnational education (TNE) to prevent reputational risks for Welsh institutions. If not managed and regulated appropriately, TNE activities can undermine the strong reputation of the Welsh sector as a whole. It is crucial for any TNE undertaken by a Welsh institution to have appropriate quality guarantees built into it.&#10;&#10;3. The Welsh government emphasizes that no changes will be made in the quality assurance regime that would risk the high reputation and standards of Welsh universities or set them apart from institutions across borders or in a European context. Concerns about this potential impact are acknowledged but considered misplaced, and addressing these concerns is essential for smooth implementation.&#10;&#10;4. To address the future growth in work-based and part-time postgraduate learning, the government will ensure that quality assurance regimes evolve accordingly. Historically, work-based learning quality assurance has been Estyn's responsibility, while university assurance regimes have fallen under the QAA's purview. Greater synergy in quality assurance and enhancement across these different areas of activity is encouraged.&#10;&#10;5. The Welsh government will maintain institutional autonomy while ensuring appropriate regulation and accountability for public funding and privileges in higher education, aiming to move things forward effectively and address emerging trends in the sector." />
    <node id=" quality assurance regimes for work-based learning have tended to sit with Estyn; the assurance regimes for the universities have sat with the QAA. There's quite a lot of learning that all sides have got to engage in if we're going to be able to have continued high quality in these new areas that are being explored. That's an issue not just in Wales. The Augar report, which was published earlier this year in England, drew attention to this as being a major problem in the relationship over the border between Ofsted and the QAA. So, I think we're not looking to impose one institution on anybody, but we are looking to encourage greater synergy in the ways in which quality assurance and enhancement is undertaken in those different areas of activity.&#10;Speaker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: And finally, therefore, looking at overseas providers. Currently, of course, universities can award their degrees to students being taught by providers overseas. We know this created problems for the University of Wales in 2011. They faced a scandal; that's probably the best word to use there. Will the new Bill address these issues?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Well, certainly transnational education does present real opportunities for Welsh institutions, but" />
