    <node id="1. Informal measures: HEFCW uses various informal methods such as providing information, holding events, and offering staff development activities to foster a culture of compliance among institution leaders and governing bodies. They also engage in dialogues with different tertiary sector stakeholders like FE college principals, work-based learning providers, and sixth forms to promote alignment with national priorities.&#10;&#10;2. Formal interventions: Under the 2015 Higher Education Act, HEFCW has been given new powers of intervention and sanctions to address non-compliance by institutions in areas such as fee limits, quality of provision, or financial management code violations. These formal measures ensure accountability for public funding and privileges that institutions enjoy while respecting their autonomy.&#10;&#10;3. Remit letters: HEFCW uses remit letters as a mechanism to clearly articulate national priorities and communicate them to higher education institutions. This allows institutions to work towards fulfilling national outcomes while maintaining their autonomy.&#10;&#10;4. Protecting institutional privileges and autonomy: The 2015 Higher Education Act contains provisions that protect universities' privileges and autonomy, which HEFCW aims to carry forward into future legislation. By respecting institutional autonomy, HEFCW encourages a collaborative relationship with institutions and stakeholders in the higher education sector.&#10;&#10;In summary, HEFCW balances the need for regulation and delivering national outcomes with respecting institutional autonomy by utilizing informal measures, formal interventions when necessary, remit letters to communicate national priorities, and protecting institutional privileges and autonomy. This approach fosters a positive working relationship between HEFCW, institutions, and stakeholders in the higher education sector." />
    <node id="1. The 2012 university funding system has limited the Welsh Government's policy leverage over the higher education sector by reducing the Higher Education Funding Council for Wales (HEFCW)'s budget, which in turn affects its ability to impose terms and conditions on institutions. The Higher Education Act of 2015 was introduced to address this shift in influence, providing HEFCW with new intervention and sanction powers to ensure compliance in areas such as fee limits, quality of provision, or financial management code violations.&#10;   &#10;2. However, the Higher Education Act does not directly address governance issues within the sector. The Act has given HEFCW more significant enforcement capabilities, but it is essential to recognize that these formal measures might not always be suitable for quick interventions, as they can be complicated and time-consuming.&#10;&#10;3. To maintain flexibility in regulation, HEFCW could consider implementing a risk-based approach focusing on riskier alternative providers while ensuring that stronger track record institutions face appropriate levels of scrutiny. This way, resources can be allocated more efficiently, addressing issues proactively rather than reactively.&#10;&#10;4. Lastly, promoting collaboration and avoiding duplication by creating a framework that encourages partnerships between different parts of post-compulsory education can help create a seamless passage for students moving between various educational opportunities and minimize barriers to entry. This will contribute to enhancing the overall sector's reputation and ensuring quality in transnational education activities." />
    <node id="1. The PCET (Post-Compulsory Education and Training) Bill could introduce a regulatory condition for good governance by giving the regulatory body, such as a commission, the power to set expectations and standards for good governance practices within higher education institutions. This could include measures to ensure that governing bodies operate in a transparent, accountable, and inclusive manner, with clear policies on issues such as conflict of interest, risk management, and stakeholder engagement.&#10;2. The concerns regarding the diversity of governance in universities' governing bodies relate to the underrepresentation of certain groups, such as women, ethnic minorities, and part-time students. According to the transcript, men make up 56% of membership of universities' governing bodies, while women account for only 44%, and BME (Black and Minority Ethnic) representation is as low as 4%. This lack of diversity may lead to biased decision-making, limited perspectives, and missed opportunities to engage with diverse communities. The Welsh Government has identified this issue as a concern and aims to address it in the PCET Bill by promoting diversity and inclusion in governance arrangements." />
    <node id=" to make sure, and they need to give confidence, that governance arrangements are what they should be.&#10;Speaker: Dawn Bowden AM&#10;Content: So, is that something that you're going to be taking into the PCET Bill, do you think?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Yes, absolutely. We're exploring how the Bill could introduce a regulatory condition in respect of good governance, and a commission would be able to set expectations with regard to good governance. I think one of the concerns for me—and I know that this is a concern that is shared by the UCU—is the diversity of governance and who finds themselves in these really important positions. HEFCW don't hold figures on it, but from an approximation that I've asked officials to do for me, currently in the universities that we have, I would say that men make up around 56 per cent of membership of universities' governing bodies; women—44 per cent; BME—as low as 4 per cent. Of course, in individual institutions, it does vary, but I think there is some way to go to making sure that our governing bodies are diverse and that there's an opportunity to look at the student voice in governance going forward, the staff voice" />
    <node id=" within institutions. For instance, as part of this Government's commitment to improving mental health, we've been able to use the remit letter and some funding to be able to drive change and some improvements in mental health in the higher education sector. These are national priorities and we're acting upon them and we're using the multiple levers we have at the moment to engage in universities. And, I have to say, universities have risen to that challenge, and I'm very grateful to them for doing that.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: Thank you. Are there plans to give the proposed new PCET funding body more effective policy levers to align the sector to the social, economic and civic needs of Wales? And, if so, how will this be done?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Well, as I said in answer earlier, I'm determined that we ensure a sense of civic mission for the entirety of the sector, including our institutes of higher education. You'll be aware, Janet, that, in the consultation exercises that have been undertaken by the Government so far on PCET reform, we will be introducing more formal outcome agreements, whereby institutions might be given by the commission very clear expectations of how they're" />
    <node id="1. Concerns of the higher education sector in Wales: The proposed move to a single quality assurance body for the tertiary education sector has raised substantial concern among Welsh vice-chancellors. They are apprehensive about potential disruptions and challenges that may arise from such a significant change. There is also fear that this change might negatively impact the high reputation and standards of Welsh universities, potentially setting them apart from institutions across borders or in a European context. The fear might be misplaced, but it is essential to address these concerns to ensure smooth implementation.&#10;&#10;2. Vice-chancellor's suggestion to cause a stir: One vice-chancellor has suggested causing a stir to bring about change, indicating dissatisfaction with the current system and emphasizing the need for effective quality assurance that addresses emerging trends in higher education. This call for change highlights concerns about the potential impact of the proposed single quality assessment body on institutional autonomy, regulation, accountability for public funding, and the maintenance of high standards in Welsh universities." />
    <node id="1. The Welsh Government plans to move towards a single quality assurance body for the tertiary education sector, which includes higher education, further education, and work-based learning. This change aims to ensure compatibility and coherence between quality assurance regimes as they converge in the tertiary sector, addressing emerging trends in higher education.&#10;2. The new plan will involve maintaining institutional autonomy while ensuring appropriate regulation and accountability for public funding and privileges in higher education, aiming to move things forward effectively and address emerging trends in the sector.&#10;3. Although further education colleges have expressed contentment with the current arrangements, the Welsh Government recognizes that a single quality assessment body is necessary to ensure high-quality provision in new areas of activity and evolving postgraduate learning formats.&#10;4. The plan also addresses concerns about transnational education (TNE) to prevent reputational risks for Welsh institutions by ensuring appropriate quality guarantees are built into TNE activities.&#10;5. While addressing the future growth in work-based and part-time postgraduate learning, the government will ensure that quality assurance regimes evolve accordingly, encouraging greater synergy in quality assurance and enhancement across different areas of activity.&#10;6. The Welsh Government emphasizes that no changes will be made in the quality assurance regime that would risk the high reputation and standards of Welsh universities or set them apart from institutions across borders or in a European context." />
    <node id="The Hazelkorn review suggests using outcome agreements as a broader measure of the range of things that higher education institutions do. This would allow for tracking of institutional performance through the provision of information back to the institution, enabling them to understand their performance. In some cases, funding may be linked to these outcomes to incentivize positive performance.&#10;&#10;The Welsh Government needs to strike a balance between using powers to direct higher education institutions and respecting their autonomy. While they are committed to protecting universities' privileges and autonomy, they also recognize the need for appropriate regulation and accountability of institutions for their public funding and the privileges they enjoy. They aim to ensure national priorities are clearly articulated through remit letters and other levers, while maintaining a positive working relationship with higher education institutions and HEFCW. The post-compulsory education and training Bill may include provisions to address these concerns." />
    <node id="'t think we're going to be going back to that system in the foreseeable future because of the pressures on public finances—&#10;Speaker: Hefin David AM&#10;Content: That wasn't how I understood it. I understood it to be the fact that you use these informal powers and then the next step up is quite a severe sanction and there's not much in between those.&#10;Speaker: Huw Morris&#10;Content: So, in—. Shall I carry on?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Of course, yes.&#10;Speaker: Huw Morris&#10;Content: In the Hazelkorn review, there's quite a lot of focus on that and looking to learn from other national systems where outcome agreements provide a broader measure of the range of things the institutions do and a mechanism for tracking how things are done through the provision of information back to the institution to help them know how they're doing. And potentially, in some of these other institutions, funding is linked to some of those things.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: And, of course, what always has to be—. What we have to strike the balance of as well is at what point those powers seem to be—and the ability to direct—" />
