    <node id="1. By utilizing informal measures such as providing information, holding events, and offering staff development activities, HEFCW fosters a culture of compliance among institution leaders and governing bodies while respecting their autonomy. They engage in dialogues with different tertiary sector stakeholders to promote alignment with national priorities.&#10;2. Through remit letters, HEFCW clearly articulates national priorities and communicates them to higher education institutions, allowing them to work towards fulfilling national outcomes while maintaining their autonomy.&#10;3. The 2015 Higher Education Act has given HEFCW new powers of intervention and sanctions to address non-compliance by institutions in areas such as fee limits, quality of provision, or financial management code violations. These formal measures ensure accountability for public funding and privileges that institutions enjoy while respecting their autonomy.&#10;4. Protecting institutional privileges and autonomy through provisions in the 2015 Higher Education Act encourages a collaborative relationship with institutions and stakeholders in the higher education sector.&#10;5. While there are no plans to mandate specific review details in the new legislation, both HEFCW and QAA play a crucial role in ensuring the quality of offshore higher education activities, helping maintain the strong reputation of Welsh institutions and the sector as a whole.&#10;6. HEFCW's focus on encouraging a &quot;civic university approach&quot; highlights their commitment to fostering positive relationships with institutions and stakeholders while delivering national outcomes." />
