    <node id="aker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: Okay. Thank you.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Okay. Thank you. Are there any other questions from Members? No. Okay. Well, can I thank you both for attending this morning and answering all our questions? As usual, you will be sent a transcript to check for accuracy following the meeting, but thank you both for your attendance this morning.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Thank you.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Item 3 then is papers to note. Paper to note 1 is a letter from the Minister for Education regarding the revised additional learning needs implementation plan. Paper to note 2 is additional information from HEFCW, following the meeting on 18 July, in relation to our post-legislative scrutiny of the Higher Education (Wales) Act. And paper to note 3 is a letter from us to the Welsh Local Government Association on the Childcare Funding (Wales) Act 2019. This is the letter that we agreed we would send last week. Can I ask Members if they're happy to note those? Yes. Thank you very much. Item 4 then. Can I propose, in accordance with Standing" />
    <node id="Based on the transcript, Kirsty Williams AM mentioned that as part of the post-compulsory education and training (PCET) reforms, the Welsh Government plans to introduce more formal outcome agreements. These agreements would provide clear expectations for higher education institutions regarding their contribution to national priorities. This is one way the new PCET funding body could be given more effective policy levers to align the sector with the social, economic, and civic needs of Wales. However, there was no explicit mention of further deep dialogue with key stakeholders like Universities Wales regarding fee and access plans since the consultation on PCET reforms closed in summer 2018." />
    <node id="Based on the information provided in the transcript, the current regulatory framework for alternative education providers in Wales, as outlined in the 2015 Act, may not adequately address potential concerns about the quality of provision in the future. This is because the regulation of alternative providers is done on a course-by-course basis, and there are currently very few private institutions in Wales offering higher education courses. However, if the landscape were to change in the future with more part-time students and private institutions being established, the current regulatory framework may not be sufficient. It's worth noting that while Kirsty Williams AM mentioned ongoing discussions with stakeholders regarding legislation development, there is no explicit mention of deep dialogue with key stakeholders like Universities Wales regarding fee and access plans since the consultation on PCET reforms closed in summer 2018. Therefore, it is unclear if potential concerns about the quality of provision for increased part-time students have been adequately addressed through these discussions." />
    <node id="Based on the transcript, the Welsh Government is planning to review and potentially amend or replace the Higher Education (Wales) Act 2015 through the post-compulsory education and training Bill. This new bill may include provisions to ensure appropriate regulation and accountability of institutions for their public funding and privileges. This could be interpreted as a measure to create a more graduated escalation process, as more robust regulation and accountability could help address issues at higher education institutions before they become more serious.&#10;&#10;Additionally, Kirsty Williams AM mentioned plans to introduce more formal outcome agreements, which would provide clear expectations for higher education institutions regarding their contribution to national priorities. This is another way the new PCET funding body could be given more effective policy levers to align the sector with the social, economic, and civic needs of Wales, and could potentially serve as an early escalation measure before more serious action needs to be taken.&#10;&#10;However, the transcript does not provide specific details about a graduated escalation process from early conversations to potentially issuing advice and guidance. It is possible that such measures may be included in the post-compulsory education and training Bill or in other aspects of the Welsh Government's higher education policy." />
