    <edge source=" new Bill address these issues?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Well, certainly transnational education does present real opportunities for Welsh institutions, but if not managed appropriately and regulated appropriately can cause real risks to reputation to our sector. When I meet with vice-chancellors in universities in different parts of the world, and when I am visiting different countries, one of the great things that I'm able to say is that we have a sector that provides fantastic quality of teaching, excellence in research and a wonderful student experience, and that is undermined if institutions find themselves undertaking TNE activities that put that at risk. So, it's an important consideration for the health of the whole sector that any TNE undertaken by a Welsh institution has the appropriate quality guarantees built into that because it's a problem not just for an individual institution, but it could undermine the very strong reputation that the Welsh sector has as a whole. Huw, was there anything further about TNE?&#10;Speaker: Huw Morris&#10;Content: Well, just to say that we are live to that, as I know HEFCW and the QAA are. We've had conversations with both in the recent past. There is quality assurance of offshore activity through the QAA. When they" target="1. The Welsh government is proposing to move towards a single quality assurance body for the tertiary education sector, which would include higher education, further education, and work-based learning. This change aims to ensure compatibility and coherence between quality assurance regimes as they converge in the tertiary sector, addressing emerging trends in higher education.&#10;&#10;2. The new Bill will address issues related to transnational education (TNE) to prevent reputational risks for Welsh institutions. If not managed and regulated appropriately, TNE activities can undermine the strong reputation of the Welsh sector as a whole. It is crucial for any TNE undertaken by a Welsh institution to have appropriate quality guarantees built into it.&#10;&#10;3. The Welsh government emphasizes that no changes will be made in the quality assurance regime that would risk the high reputation and standards of Welsh universities or set them apart from institutions across borders or in a European context. Concerns about this potential impact are acknowledged but considered misplaced, and addressing these concerns is essential for smooth implementation.&#10;&#10;4. To address the future growth in work-based and part-time postgraduate learning, the government will ensure that quality assurance regimes evolve accordingly. Historically, work-based learning quality assurance has been Estyn's responsibility, while university assurance regimes have fallen under the QAA's purview. Greater synergy in quality assurance and enhancement across these different areas of activity is encouraged.&#10;&#10;5. The Welsh government will maintain institutional autonomy while ensuring appropriate regulation and accountability for public funding and privileges in higher education, aiming to move things forward effectively and address emerging trends in the sector.">
