    <edge source=". But, at this current moment, the Act precludes fee regulation in some areas and there's not a pressing policy need that we've identified to date.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Okay. Thank you. Okay, we're going to move on now to some questions about the level of ambition in the higher education Act and any lessons for the PCET Bill, from Janet Finch-Saunders.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: Thank you. To what extent has the 2012 university funding system limited Welsh Government’s policy leverage over the sector, and how has the HE Act addressed this beyond the levers offered by fee and access plans?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Of course, the Act was introduced as a direct result of the changing scenario around finance and the different ways in which, because of the reduction in HEFCW's budget, the level of influence that HEFCW would be able to exert over institutions through the imposition of terms and conditions of funding—. So, the Act was introduced in part to address that shift in influence and the Act also has provided HEFCW with a range of new powers of intervention and sanctions in the case of non-compliance by institutions" target="1. Yes, the speaker Kirsty Williams AM agrees that the four strategic aims of the Act, which are regulation of institutions, safeguarding public good, ensuring fair access, and preserving institutional autonomy, are still important objectives for higher education in Wales. She mentions that these aims will underpin their thought process going forward and will be carried into the forthcoming Bill. She also acknowledges the importance of appropriate regulation and accountability of institutions for their public funding and privileges they enjoy.&#10;&#10;2. This agreement is expressed in the context of the implementation of the new student support measures in Wales and the higher education and research Bill across the border in England, which makes it crucial for Wales to have its own legislation that ensures a positive environment for the development of the higher education sector in the country. The speaker also agrees that these objectives are relevant in light of the need to manage risks and ensure appropriate regulation and accountability of institutions for their public funding and privileges they enjoy.&#10;&#10;3. However, there is some disagreement on whether the current legislation has been framed around institutional autonomy in a way that makes it impossible for institutions to fulfill national outcomes. The speaker Kirsty Williams AM argues that there are provisions in the 2015 Act that protect universities' privileges and autonomy, which she is committed to carrying forward into the forthcoming Bill. She also emphasizes the importance of the remit letter as a mechanism for ensuring that national priorities are clearly articulated and implemented by the Higher Education Funding Council for Wales (HEFCW).&#10;&#10;4. Overall, while there may be differences in opinion on the effectiveness of the current legislation, there is agreement that regulation of institutions, safeguarding public good, ensuring fair access, and preserving institutional autonomy are important objectives for higher education in Wales, especially in light of the higher education and research Bill in England and new student support measures in Wales. The forthcoming Bill will aim to strengthen or add more provisions to achieve these objectives while also ensuring appropriate regulation and accountability of institutions for their public funding and privileges they enjoy.">
