    <edge source=". But, at this current moment, the Act precludes fee regulation in some areas and there's not a pressing policy need that we've identified to date.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Okay. Thank you. Okay, we're going to move on now to some questions about the level of ambition in the higher education Act and any lessons for the PCET Bill, from Janet Finch-Saunders.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: Thank you. To what extent has the 2012 university funding system limited Welsh Government’s policy leverage over the sector, and how has the HE Act addressed this beyond the levers offered by fee and access plans?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Of course, the Act was introduced as a direct result of the changing scenario around finance and the different ways in which, because of the reduction in HEFCW's budget, the level of influence that HEFCW would be able to exert over institutions through the imposition of terms and conditions of funding—. So, the Act was introduced in part to address that shift in influence and the Act also has provided HEFCW with a range of new powers of intervention and sanctions in the case of non-compliance by institutions" target="1. The 2012 university funding system has limited the Welsh Government's policy leverage over the higher education sector by reducing the Higher Education Funding Council for Wales (HEFCW)'s budget, which in turn affects its ability to impose terms and conditions on institutions. The Higher Education Act of 2015 was introduced to address this shift in influence, providing HEFCW with new intervention and sanction powers to ensure compliance in areas such as fee limits, quality of provision, or financial management code violations.&#10;   &#10;2. However, the Higher Education Act does not directly address governance issues within the sector. The Act has given HEFCW more significant enforcement capabilities, but it is essential to recognize that these formal measures might not always be suitable for quick interventions, as they can be complicated and time-consuming.&#10;&#10;3. To maintain flexibility in regulation, HEFCW could consider implementing a risk-based approach focusing on riskier alternative providers while ensuring that stronger track record institutions face appropriate levels of scrutiny. This way, resources can be allocated more efficiently, addressing issues proactively rather than reactively.&#10;&#10;4. Lastly, promoting collaboration and avoiding duplication by creating a framework that encourages partnerships between different parts of post-compulsory education can help create a seamless passage for students moving between various educational opportunities and minimize barriers to entry. This will contribute to enhancing the overall sector's reputation and ensuring quality in transnational education activities.">
