    <edge source=", our expectation on HEFCW is to ensure that they are using their powers to support those universities, and I would expect them, if they felt necessary, to use the full remit of their powers if they felt that that was what they needed to do. Now, I have to trust their professional judgment that that has not been necessary to date, but our expectation is that they would do that if they felt it was necessary.&#10;Speaker: Dawn Bowden AM&#10;Content: Okay. Thank you. Thank you, Chair.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Hefin David has some questions now on fee and access plans.&#10;Speaker: Hefin David AM&#10;Content: Are you concerned that neither the regulator nor the sector seem to have any confidence in fee and access plans?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: I think the concept of a fee and access plan is an important concept. Whether we can do them better, whether we can reflect on what's happened to date and create a better system of what's included in a fee and access plan and how those fee and access plans can be monitored, there's an opportunity to do that in forthcoming legislation.&#10;Speaker: Hefin David AM&#10;Content:" target="1. Purpose and Potential Benefit: The Welsh Government is considering incorporating fee and access plans into outcome agreements as part of a wider effort to change the nature of people who go to university and ensure that nobody is put off from pursuing higher education. The goal is to shift the focus from the inputs of the activity (how much money is spent on fee and access plans) to the outputs and outcomes (what are the results of the fee and access plan). This approach would allow for a more effective evaluation of the success of these plans.&#10;2. Making Fee and Access Plans More Effective: To make fee and access plans more effective, there is a need to restructure the current format, which focuses on yearly plans and bureaucratic processes. Instead, shifting to longer-term plans with an outcome focus would provide a better way of achieving the intended goals. This change could be implemented through forthcoming legislation, allowing for improved monitoring and evaluation of fee and access plans' success.&#10;&#10;In summary, integrating fee and access plans into outcome agreements can help shift the focus from inputs to outputs, making it easier to assess their effectiveness. To achieve this, a restructuring of the current format is required, moving towards longer-term, outcome-focused plans that can be effectively monitored and evaluated through legislation.">
