    <edge source="1. Concerns about the proposal to move to one assurance body: There is substantial concern in the higher education sector in Wales about this proposal, with some vice-chancellors expressing apprehension. They worry about potential disruptions and challenges that may arise from such a significant change.&#10;2. Satisfaction with current arrangements: Further education colleges have generally been content with the current arrangements for quality assurance. They have adapted to new ways of working as they become more involved in higher education, indicating a level of comfort with the existing system.&#10;3. Fear of misplaced fear: Some stakeholders express concern that the proposed single quality assessment body might negatively impact the high reputation and standards of Welsh universities, potentially setting them apart from institutions across borders or in a European context. This fear may be misplaced, but it is essential to address these concerns to ensure smooth implementation.&#10;4. Futureproofing: The growth in postgraduate and part-time students engaging in higher education in non-traditional settings necessitates a reconsideration of quality assurance regimes. Historically, work-based learning quality assurance has been Estyn's responsibility, while university assurance regimes have fallen under the QAA's purview. The proposal aims to ensure compatibility and coherence between these systems as they converge in the tertiary sector.&#10;5. Need for change: Kirsty Williams AM suggests that changing the current system might be necessary to move things forward and ensure effective quality assurance that addresses emerging trends in higher education. She emphasizes her commitment to maintaining institutional autonomy while ensuring appropriate regulation and accountability for public funding and privileges." target="1. The Welsh government is proposing to move towards a single quality assurance body for the tertiary education sector, which would include higher education, further education, and work-based learning. This change aims to ensure compatibility and coherence between quality assurance regimes as they converge in the tertiary sector, addressing emerging trends in higher education.&#10;&#10;2. The new Bill will address issues related to transnational education (TNE) to prevent reputational risks for Welsh institutions. If not managed and regulated appropriately, TNE activities can undermine the strong reputation of the Welsh sector as a whole. It is crucial for any TNE undertaken by a Welsh institution to have appropriate quality guarantees built into it.&#10;&#10;3. The Welsh government emphasizes that no changes will be made in the quality assurance regime that would risk the high reputation and standards of Welsh universities or set them apart from institutions across borders or in a European context. Concerns about this potential impact are acknowledged but considered misplaced, and addressing these concerns is essential for smooth implementation.&#10;&#10;4. To address the future growth in work-based and part-time postgraduate learning, the government will ensure that quality assurance regimes evolve accordingly. Historically, work-based learning quality assurance has been Estyn's responsibility, while university assurance regimes have fallen under the QAA's purview. Greater synergy in quality assurance and enhancement across these different areas of activity is encouraged.&#10;&#10;5. The Welsh government will maintain institutional autonomy while ensuring appropriate regulation and accountability for public funding and privileges in higher education, aiming to move things forward effectively and address emerging trends in the sector.">
