    <edge source="y Williams AM&#10;Content: Certainly, I see the remit letter as a really, really important way in which national priorities and the priorities of an elected Government can be clearly stated, communicated to the Higher Education Funding Council for Wales, and then HEFCW use their powers to ensure that that happens. So, certainly, I see the remit letter as being a very important mechanism for ensuring, as I said, that those national priorities are clearly articulated, and then change happens.&#10;Speaker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: Has the current legislation been framed around institutional autonomy so that it's not possible for institutions to fulfil any national outcomes, and is that going to be an element of the new Bill?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Well, certainly, the 2015 Act contains numerous provisions that protect universities' privileges and autonomy. And that's really important, and those are principles that I am committed to in any legislation that I bring forward. We'll certainly be looking to see how we can carry those protections into the forthcoming Bill, but, at the same time, we do have to ensure appropriate regulation and accountability of institutions for their public funding and the privileges that they enjoy. And I think there are a number of ways in" target="1. Informal measures: HEFCW uses various informal methods such as providing information, holding events, and offering staff development activities to foster a culture of compliance among institution leaders and governing bodies. They also engage in dialogues with different tertiary sector stakeholders like FE college principals, work-based learning providers, and sixth forms to promote alignment with national priorities.&#10;&#10;2. Formal interventions: Under the 2015 Higher Education Act, HEFCW has been given new powers of intervention and sanctions to address non-compliance by institutions in areas such as fee limits, quality of provision, or financial management code violations. These formal measures ensure accountability for public funding and privileges that institutions enjoy while respecting their autonomy.&#10;&#10;3. Remit letters: HEFCW uses remit letters as a mechanism to clearly articulate national priorities and communicate them to higher education institutions. This allows institutions to work towards fulfilling national outcomes while maintaining their autonomy.&#10;&#10;4. Protecting institutional privileges and autonomy: The 2015 Higher Education Act contains provisions that protect universities' privileges and autonomy, which HEFCW aims to carry forward into future legislation. By respecting institutional autonomy, HEFCW encourages a collaborative relationship with institutions and stakeholders in the higher education sector.&#10;&#10;In summary, HEFCW balances the need for regulation and delivering national outcomes with respecting institutional autonomy by utilizing informal measures, formal interventions when necessary, remit letters to communicate national priorities, and protecting institutional privileges and autonomy. This approach fosters a positive working relationship between HEFCW, institutions, and stakeholders in the higher education sector.">
