    <edge source="1. Soft Regulatory Powers: The new commission should have the ability to offer advice and guidance to institutions as a non-punitive form of intervention. This could include enhanced monitoring of institutions to ensure compliance with regulatory conditions, providing support and allowing people to go in and help institutions.&#10;&#10;2. Graduated Series of Actions: The new system should move away from the current three-step approach and develop a more flexible graduated series of actions that the commission can take. This would enable the commission to intervene in a manner that suits the specific situation, ensuring quality or financial stability without immediately resorting to punitive measures.&#10;&#10;3. Punitive Interventions: While non-punitive interventions should be prioritized, the new regulatory framework must also allow for more punitive actions if institutions are deemed to be at risk of providing poor quality education or experiencing financial failure. This would maintain a balance between institutional autonomy and regulatory intervention while protecting students' interests and the reputation of Welsh institutions.&#10;&#10;4. Formal Outcome Agreements: Introducing formal outcome agreements as part of the new legislation would help define expectations for how institutions contribute to national priorities, allowing the commission to enforce compliance when necessary.&#10;&#10;5. Strengthening Governance: The new Act should consider addressing the issue of poor governance directly rather than merely responding to its symptoms. This could involve setting guidelines or requirements related to good governance practices in higher education institutions.&#10;&#10;The new Bill, as mentioned by Hefin David AM and Kirsty Williams AM, should aim to strike a balance between institutional autonomy and regulatory intervention, providing the commission with soft and flexible powers for non-punitive interventions while also allowing for punitive actions when necessary. By introducing formal outcome agreements and addressing governance issues directly in the new legislation, the Welsh government can ensure quality and financial stability in institutions more effectively than the current system." target=" Well, looking ahead to the new Bill, I would want to see and be very keen to ensure that there are sufficiently flexible—did you use the word soft—and soft regulatory powers that the commission could exercise. Those powers, for instance, could include the ability to offer advice and guidance, rather than, maybe, punitive interventions, and powers to undertake enhanced monitoring of institutions to ensure compliance with regulatory conditions. So, I would expect the commission to be able to have a series of abilities to intervene, from the soft, flexible type, which is non-punitive but actually allows people to go in and support institutions, through to something that would be, as I said, more punitive, if they felt that an institution was in danger of not providing quality or financial failure.&#10;Speaker: Hefin David AM&#10;Content: Can I just come in there, on the point that was made? The issue that seemed to me to come from HEFCW and from the universities is that the dial seems to have only three steps. So, rather than having a graduated series of actions that they can take, it seems to step from—what did he call it—a 'meeting without coffee' to—&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: That">
