    <edge source="1. Soft Regulatory Powers: The new commission should have the ability to offer advice and guidance to institutions as a non-punitive form of intervention. This could include enhanced monitoring of institutions to ensure compliance with regulatory conditions, providing support and allowing people to go in and help institutions.&#10;&#10;2. Graduated Series of Actions: The new system should move away from the current three-step approach and develop a more flexible graduated series of actions that the commission can take. This would enable the commission to intervene in a manner that suits the specific situation, ensuring quality or financial stability without immediately resorting to punitive measures.&#10;&#10;3. Punitive Interventions: While non-punitive interventions should be prioritized, the new regulatory framework must also allow for more punitive actions if institutions are deemed to be at risk of providing poor quality education or experiencing financial failure. This would maintain a balance between institutional autonomy and regulatory intervention while protecting students' interests and the reputation of Welsh institutions.&#10;&#10;4. Formal Outcome Agreements: Introducing formal outcome agreements as part of the new legislation would help define expectations for how institutions contribute to national priorities, allowing the commission to enforce compliance when necessary.&#10;&#10;5. Strengthening Governance: The new Act should consider addressing the issue of poor governance directly rather than merely responding to its symptoms. This could involve setting guidelines or requirements related to good governance practices in higher education institutions.&#10;&#10;The new Bill, as mentioned by Hefin David AM and Kirsty Williams AM, should aim to strike a balance between institutional autonomy and regulatory intervention, providing the commission with soft and flexible powers for non-punitive interventions while also allowing for punitive actions when necessary. By introducing formal outcome agreements and addressing governance issues directly in the new legislation, the Welsh government can ensure quality and financial stability in institutions more effectively than the current system." target=" always has to be—. What we have to strike the balance of as well is at what point those powers seem to be—and the ability to direct—interfering with the principle of autonomy within an institution. So, there's that balance to be struck, isn't there, about creating a regulatory regime, which I'm very keen and the Act attempted to do, which was to enshrine institutional autonomy, and that's really, really important, but also a regulatory regime, the ability to influence and to develop and to deliver national outcomes and the power to intervene in that sector, which you know, better than probably anybody else in this room, guards that institutional autonomy very, very, very dear indeed. And that's the balance that we need to try and strike as we go forward with the new commission proposals.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Okay. Thank you. Dawn.&#10;Speaker: Dawn Bowden AM&#10;Content: Thank you, Chair. I think, in terms of the levels of measures—and I understand what you're saying—but I think what HEFCW were saying was that they try as far as possible to use informal measures and they are able to do that because of the size of the sector">
