    <edge source="1. Regulation and Quality: Private institutions, as compared to public institutions, operate with less rigor and are subject to less regulation. This is because they do not have to adhere to the same standards or comply with the same level of scrutiny. The QAA, in cooperation with institutions, reviews and inspects offshore higher education activities; however, there is no plan to mandate specific review details in the new legislation.&#10;&#10;2. Role of Charitable Status: Many private institutions are also charities, which receive less attention in discussions about regulation. Charitable status is an important reference point for the operation of these institutions. Some private providers, especially in England, have faced issues related to fee limits, quality of provision, and financial management code violations, leading to intervention and sanctions from HEFCW under the 2015 Higher Education Act.&#10;&#10;3. Viewing Private Institutions: When considering the interests of students, it's important to be cautious about tarring all private providers with the same brush, as some may provide high-quality education despite their private status. The new legislation should consider this nuance and focus on the inherent quality of institutions rather than their categorization as public or private.&#10;&#10;4. Managing Risk: With the 2015 Act in place, institutions with stronger track records are more highly regulated compared to riskier alternative providers. This balance should be maintained, as legislation should strike a proportionality based on the amount and nature of public money received by institutions. The new legislation will look to create a system of outcome agreements where outputs will reflect national priorities.&#10;&#10;In conclusion, when discussing private versus public institutions, it is essential to consider charitable status, inherent quality, track records, and the balance between regulation and proportionality based on public funding. The new legislation must strike a careful balance that protects students' interests while fostering an environment conducive to broadening access in higher education." target=" is proportionate, myself.&#10;Speaker: Hefin David AM&#10;Content: So, do you think it's in the interests of students, then, to be at private institutions—? I've seen those private institutions and how they operate; I've seen them at first-hand—they don't operate to the same rigour as public institutions, and they're less regulated.&#10;Speaker: Huw Morris&#10;Content: Can I just chip in? I think that the category 'private' covers quite a wide range of things, and many private institutions are also charities. We don't have the presence of some of the large private charities that are present in other countries, but Stanford and Harvard would count as private universities. So, I think we need to be careful in focusing on the inherent quality of things. We've made charitable status a key reference point in the operation of things at the moment. I think there has been attention drawn to some private providers, particularly in England, but I wouldn't tar them all with the same brush, necessarily.&#10;Speaker: Hefin David AM&#10;Content: But they fall outwith—if they're not charitable providers running validated courses, for example, they fall outwith the strength of regulation that is currently in">
