    <edge source="1. HEFCW is encouraging a &quot;civic university approach&quot; by providing information, holding events, and offering staff, management, and leadership development activities to create a culture among institution leaders and governing bodies that moves them in this direction. They use informal interactions with various tertiary sector stakeholders such as FE college principals, work-based learning providers, and sixth forms to foster alignment with the civic university approach.&#10;2. Although there is no plan to mandate specific review details in the new legislation, HEFCW and QAA play a crucial role in ensuring the quality of offshore higher education activities. This helps maintain the strong reputation of Welsh institutions and the sector as a whole.&#10;3. The 2015 Higher Education Act has given HEFCW new powers to intervene and enforce compliance when necessary, including issues related to fee limits, quality of provision, or financial management code violations. However, governance issues in the sector are not directly addressed by the Act.&#10;4. In summary, HEFCW uses various measures to foster a civic university approach, focusing on cooperation with institutions and stakeholders. The 2015 Higher Education Act has provided new intervention powers, but there is no return to the block grant allocation system." target="1. The 2012 university funding system has limited the Welsh Government's policy leverage over the higher education sector by reducing the Higher Education Funding Council for Wales (HEFCW)'s budget, which in turn affects its ability to impose terms and conditions on institutions. The Higher Education Act of 2015 was introduced to address this shift in influence, providing HEFCW with new intervention and sanction powers to ensure compliance in areas such as fee limits, quality of provision, or financial management code violations.&#10;   &#10;2. However, the Higher Education Act does not directly address governance issues within the sector. The Act has given HEFCW more significant enforcement capabilities, but it is essential to recognize that these formal measures might not always be suitable for quick interventions, as they can be complicated and time-consuming.&#10;&#10;3. To maintain flexibility in regulation, HEFCW could consider implementing a risk-based approach focusing on riskier alternative providers while ensuring that stronger track record institutions face appropriate levels of scrutiny. This way, resources can be allocated more efficiently, addressing issues proactively rather than reactively.&#10;&#10;4. Lastly, promoting collaboration and avoiding duplication by creating a framework that encourages partnerships between different parts of post-compulsory education can help create a seamless passage for students moving between various educational opportunities and minimize barriers to entry. This will contribute to enhancing the overall sector's reputation and ensuring quality in transnational education activities.">
