    <edge source="1. Purpose and Potential Benefit: The Welsh Government is considering incorporating fee and access plans into outcome agreements as part of a wider effort to change the nature of people who go to university and ensure that nobody is put off from pursuing higher education. The goal is to shift the focus from the inputs of the activity (how much money is spent on fee and access plans) to the outputs and outcomes (what are the results of the fee and access plan). This approach would allow for a more effective evaluation of the success of these plans.&#10;2. Making Fee and Access Plans More Effective: To make fee and access plans more effective, there is a need to restructure the current format, which focuses on yearly plans and bureaucratic processes. Instead, shifting to longer-term plans with an outcome focus would provide a better way of achieving the intended goals. This change could be implemented through forthcoming legislation, allowing for improved monitoring and evaluation of fee and access plans' success.&#10;&#10;In summary, integrating fee and access plans into outcome agreements can help shift the focus from inputs to outputs, making it easier to assess their effectiveness. To achieve this, a restructuring of the current format is required, moving towards longer-term, outcome-focused plans that can be effectively monitored and evaluated through legislation." target="'s plan. So, I think there's an opportunity there to look to restructure. So, do I see a place for fee and access plans going forward, as part of our outcome agreements? Yes, I do. Can we do them differently to make them more effective? Yes, I think we can.&#10;Speaker: Hefin David AM&#10;Content: So, why would introducing outcome agreements make them work any better?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Well, I think they're going to be a part of an outcome agreement—part of that wider expectation. So, fee and access plans are there to address an issue around, primarily, changing the nature of people who go to university and making sure that nobody is put off from pursuing that. So, that's part of a wider piece of work that I'd want to see as an outcome agreement. But, as I said, I think looking at outcomes for students and outcomes of that activity, rather than the inputs of the activity, over a longer period of time, is probably a more effective way of doing it. I think it's still—. In a way, it's difficult to make a final judgment on whether fee and access plans in their current format have worked, because">
