    <edge source="Based on the meeting transcript, the Welsh Government does not explicitly mention any specific measures to address the gap between early conversations and the possibility of institutions going bankrupt in the tertiary education sector. However, they do plan to review and potentially amend or replace the Higher Education (Wales) Act 2015 through the post-compulsory education and training Bill. This new bill may include provisions to ensure appropriate regulation and accountability of institutions for their public funding and privileges, which could potentially address some of the concerns around institutional bankruptcy. The government also emphasizes the importance of a positive working relationship with higher education institutions and HEFCW, as well as using mechanisms like remit letters to clearly articulate national priorities." target="1. The 2012 university funding system has limited the Welsh Government's policy leverage over the higher education sector by reducing the Higher Education Funding Council for Wales (HEFCW)'s budget, which in turn affects its ability to impose terms and conditions on institutions. The Higher Education Act of 2015 was introduced to address this shift in influence, providing HEFCW with new intervention and sanction powers to ensure compliance in areas such as fee limits, quality of provision, or financial management code violations.&#10;   &#10;2. However, the Higher Education Act does not directly address governance issues within the sector. The Act has given HEFCW more significant enforcement capabilities, but it is essential to recognize that these formal measures might not always be suitable for quick interventions, as they can be complicated and time-consuming.&#10;&#10;3. To maintain flexibility in regulation, HEFCW could consider implementing a risk-based approach focusing on riskier alternative providers while ensuring that stronger track record institutions face appropriate levels of scrutiny. This way, resources can be allocated more efficiently, addressing issues proactively rather than reactively.&#10;&#10;4. Lastly, promoting collaboration and avoiding duplication by creating a framework that encourages partnerships between different parts of post-compulsory education can help create a seamless passage for students moving between various educational opportunities and minimize barriers to entry. This will contribute to enhancing the overall sector's reputation and ensuring quality in transnational education activities.">
