    <edge source="1. The Welsh government is proposing to move towards a single quality assurance body for the tertiary education sector, which would include higher education, further education, and work-based learning. This change aims to ensure compatibility and coherence between quality assurance regimes as they converge in the tertiary sector, addressing emerging trends in higher education.&#10;&#10;2. The new Bill will address issues related to transnational education (TNE) to prevent reputational risks for Welsh institutions. If not managed and regulated appropriately, TNE activities can undermine the strong reputation of the Welsh sector as a whole. It is crucial for any TNE undertaken by a Welsh institution to have appropriate quality guarantees built into it.&#10;&#10;3. The Welsh government emphasizes that no changes will be made in the quality assurance regime that would risk the high reputation and standards of Welsh universities or set them apart from institutions across borders or in a European context. Concerns about this potential impact are acknowledged but considered misplaced, and addressing these concerns is essential for smooth implementation.&#10;&#10;4. To address the future growth in work-based and part-time postgraduate learning, the government will ensure that quality assurance regimes evolve accordingly. Historically, work-based learning quality assurance has been Estyn's responsibility, while university assurance regimes have fallen under the QAA's purview. Greater synergy in quality assurance and enhancement across these different areas of activity is encouraged.&#10;&#10;5. The Welsh government will maintain institutional autonomy while ensuring appropriate regulation and accountability for public funding and privileges in higher education, aiming to move things forward effectively and address emerging trends in the sector." target="1. Concerns of the higher education sector in Wales: The proposed move to a single quality assurance body for the tertiary education sector has raised substantial concern among Welsh vice-chancellors. They are apprehensive about potential disruptions and challenges that may arise from such a significant change. There is also fear that this change might negatively impact the high reputation and standards of Welsh universities, potentially setting them apart from institutions across borders or in a European context. The fear might be misplaced, but it is essential to address these concerns to ensure smooth implementation.&#10;&#10;2. Vice-chancellor's suggestion to cause a stir: One vice-chancellor has suggested causing a stir to bring about change, indicating dissatisfaction with the current system and emphasizing the need for effective quality assurance that addresses emerging trends in higher education. This call for change highlights concerns about the potential impact of the proposed single quality assessment body on institutional autonomy, regulation, accountability for public funding, and the maintenance of high standards in Welsh universities.">
