    <edge source="The Welsh government has not identified an urgent reason or pressing policy need to regulate part-time and postgraduate fees through fee limits in the new legislation because the current Act, the 2015 Act, does not permit fee regulation for most postgraduate courses. In the case of part-time courses, the government is currently content that fee levels are not exceeding the amount of student support made available by the Welsh Government. The success of attracting people to postgraduate and part-time study in Wales is due to the reforms to student finance, which the government wants to continue supporting. While they will keep this issue under review, there is no current review of this policy mentioned in the transcript." target="Based on the information provided in the transcript, the current regulatory framework for alternative education providers in Wales, as outlined in the 2015 Act, may not adequately address potential concerns about the quality of provision in the future. This is because the regulation of alternative providers is done on a course-by-course basis, and there are currently very few private institutions in Wales offering higher education courses. However, if the landscape were to change in the future with more part-time students and private institutions being established, the current regulatory framework may not be sufficient. It's worth noting that while Kirsty Williams AM mentioned ongoing discussions with stakeholders regarding legislation development, there is no explicit mention of deep dialogue with key stakeholders like Universities Wales regarding fee and access plans since the consultation on PCET reforms closed in summer 2018. Therefore, it is unclear if potential concerns about the quality of provision for increased part-time students have been adequately addressed through these discussions.">
