n, holding events, offering staff development activities, engaging in dialogues with stakeholders, and leveraging remit letters to foster a culture of compliance among institution leaders and governing bodies while promoting alignment with national priorities. These measures respect institutional autonomy and create a collaborative relationship between HEFCW, institutions, and sector stakeholders.&#10;&#10;2. The 2015 Higher Education Act has given HEFCW new powers of intervention and sanctions to address non-compliance by institutions in areas such as fee limits, quality of provision, or financial management code violations. Although formal measures can be cumbersome and time-consuming, they ensure accountability for public funding and privileges that institutions enjoy while respecting their autonomy.&#10;&#10;3. By implementing a risk-based approach to regulation, HEFCW focuses on riskier alternative providers while ensuring appropriate levels of scrutiny for stronger track record institutions, allocating resources efficiently and addressing issues proactively rather than reactively. This balance helps maintain flexibility in regulation and cater to the diverse needs of the expanding tertiary education sector in Wales.&#10;&#10;4. HEFCW encourages a &quot;civic university approach,&quot; further fostering positive relationships with institutions and stakeholders while delivering national outcomes, ensuring that institutional autonomy is upheld as much as possible.&#10;&#10;5. In forthcoming legislation, the Welsh Government aims to strike a balance between using powers to direct higher education institutions and respecting their autonomy by clearly articulating national priorities through remit letters and other levers, maintaining a positive working relationship with higher education institutions and HEFCW. The post-compulsory education and training Bill may include provisions addressing concerns around regulation, accountability, and high standards in Welsh universities without compromising institutional autonomy.">
