    <edge source="1. The PCET (Post-Compulsory Education and Training) Bill could introduce a regulatory condition for good governance by giving the regulatory body, such as a commission, the power to set expectations and standards for good governance practices within higher education institutions. This could include measures to ensure that governing bodies operate in a transparent, accountable, and inclusive manner, with clear policies on issues such as conflict of interest, risk management, and stakeholder engagement.&#10;2. The concerns regarding the diversity of governance in universities' governing bodies relate to the underrepresentation of certain groups, such as women, ethnic minorities, and part-time students. According to the transcript, men make up 56% of membership of universities' governing bodies, while women account for only 44%, and BME (Black and Minority Ethnic) representation is as low as 4%. This lack of diversity may lead to biased decision-making, limited perspectives, and missed opportunities to engage with diverse communities. The Welsh Government has identified this issue as a concern and aims to address it in the PCET Bill by promoting diversity and inclusion in governance arrangements." target=" to make sure, and they need to give confidence, that governance arrangements are what they should be.&#10;Speaker: Dawn Bowden AM&#10;Content: So, is that something that you're going to be taking into the PCET Bill, do you think?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Yes, absolutely. We're exploring how the Bill could introduce a regulatory condition in respect of good governance, and a commission would be able to set expectations with regard to good governance. I think one of the concerns for me—and I know that this is a concern that is shared by the UCU—is the diversity of governance and who finds themselves in these really important positions. HEFCW don't hold figures on it, but from an approximation that I've asked officials to do for me, currently in the universities that we have, I would say that men make up around 56 per cent of membership of universities' governing bodies; women—44 per cent; BME—as low as 4 per cent. Of course, in individual institutions, it does vary, but I think there is some way to go to making sure that our governing bodies are diverse and that there's an opportunity to look at the student voice in governance going forward, the staff voice">
