    <edge source="1. Concerns of the higher education sector in Wales: The proposed move to a single quality assurance body for the tertiary education sector has raised substantial concern among Welsh vice-chancellors. They are apprehensive about potential disruptions and challenges that may arise from such a significant change. There is also fear that this change might negatively impact the high reputation and standards of Welsh universities, potentially setting them apart from institutions across borders or in a European context. The fear might be misplaced, but it is essential to address these concerns to ensure smooth implementation.&#10;&#10;2. Vice-chancellor's suggestion to cause a stir: One vice-chancellor has suggested causing a stir to bring about change, indicating dissatisfaction with the current system and emphasizing the need for effective quality assurance that addresses emerging trends in higher education. This call for change highlights concerns about the potential impact of the proposed single quality assessment body on institutional autonomy, regulation, accountability for public funding, and the maintenance of high standards in Welsh universities." target="1. The Welsh Government plans to move towards a single quality assurance body for the tertiary education sector, which includes higher education, further education, and work-based learning. This change aims to ensure compatibility and coherence between quality assurance regimes as they converge in the tertiary sector, addressing emerging trends in higher education.&#10;2. The new plan will involve maintaining institutional autonomy while ensuring appropriate regulation and accountability for public funding and privileges in higher education, aiming to move things forward effectively and address emerging trends in the sector.&#10;3. Although further education colleges have expressed contentment with the current arrangements, the Welsh Government recognizes that a single quality assessment body is necessary to ensure high-quality provision in new areas of activity and evolving postgraduate learning formats.&#10;4. The plan also addresses concerns about transnational education (TNE) to prevent reputational risks for Welsh institutions by ensuring appropriate quality guarantees are built into TNE activities.&#10;5. While addressing the future growth in work-based and part-time postgraduate learning, the government will ensure that quality assurance regimes evolve accordingly, encouraging greater synergy in quality assurance and enhancement across different areas of activity.&#10;6. The Welsh Government emphasizes that no changes will be made in the quality assurance regime that would risk the high reputation and standards of Welsh universities or set them apart from institutions across borders or in a European context.">
